article.headline: (13) MINNESOTA 59, WISCONSIN 45
article.story:
MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Lindsay Whalen is an offensive threat not
many teams can handle -- and this time Wisconsin was her victim.

The senior guard scored 24 points and grabbed nine rebounds to
lead No. 14 Minnesota to a 59-48 win over Wisconsin Sunday.

Whalen shot 10-of-18 from the field for the Gophers (17-3, 7-3
Big Ten), who shot 42.6 percent in the game, well below their
average of 51 percent. The point total was also 16 below their
season average.

Minnesota coach Pam Borton said Whalen's nine rebounds were a
big factor in the game. The Badgers averaged 16 offensive rebounds
a game coming in but got just five.

"We knew we were going to have our hands full against
Wisconsin," Borton said. "That's where Lindsay really helped us
out, was on the boards."

Janel McCarville had 13 rebounds for the Gophers, who controlled
the boards 35-28.

Lello Gebisa had 13 points and 11 rebounds for her fifth
double-double of the season for the Badgers (8-11, 2-7). She had 10
boards in the second half.

Minnesota trailed just once, 13-11 midway through the first
half, and got a boost at the end when McCarville scored twice on
putbacks. The second tip-in gave the Gophers a 26-19 lead at the
break.

"I think Janel's tip there going into halftime was kind of a
momentum swing for us," said Minnesota coach Pam Borton. "It kind
of got us going for the rest of the game."

Minnesota held Wisconsin to one basket on eight possessions
during a six-minute span at the midpoint of the second half. Jamie
Broback hit a 3-pointer with 7:12 left to give the Gophers a 50-40
lead.

Shannon Schonrock added 10 points for Minnesota. Ashley
Josephson had 13 points for Wisconsin.

"We've been battling," said Wisconsin coach Lisa Stone. "Our
effort is tremendous. We're having a little trouble putting the
ball in the basket right now, but with six turnovers at the half
and finishing with just 16 against a great team is certainly
newsworthy."
